[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    29[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mA few things worth knowing upfront:[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    30[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    31[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mNo real claims warehouse integration in this example.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The adjudicated-claims source is the long pole in any production deployment, and each payer stores them differently (Redshift, Snowflake, an Athena-over-Parquet lake, or a vendor-provided warehouse). This example starts from a pandas DataFrame that looks like the output of a normalized claims query. In production, a Glue job reads from the warehouse on a monthly cadence and writes Parquet to S3.[K
