[38;5;252m[1m## What's in the preface[0m[0m
[0m[0m
The preface follows the established CC-voice and structure used in chapters 2-4:[0m[0m
[0m[0m
- **Hook:** The "Maria Garcia" scenario, illustrating why entity resolution is genuinely hard in American healthcare[0m[0m
- **What it actually is:** Definition, alternate names, and the three approaches (deterministic, probabilistic, ML-based) that drive different architectures[0m[0m
- **Why healthcare is uniquely bad at this:** Six healthcare-specific friction points including the explicit US prohibition on a national patient identifier (Section 510), name instability, family confounders, asymmetric cost of false merges vs. false splits, privacy constraints, and varying stakes[0m[0m
- **Progression simple → complex:** Brief tour of all 10 recipes (5.1 internal dedup through 5.10 deceased patient resolution) grouped by complexity tier[0m[0m
- **Technique families:** String similarity, Fellegi-Sunter probabilistic linkage, blocking/candidate generation, ML classifiers, embeddings, cryptographic methods, graph methods[0m[0m
- **Architectural patterns:** Match-score-plus-review-queue, survivorship rules, MPI/EMPI, audit/reversibility, real-time vs. batch, feedback loops, confidence-aware downstream consumption[0m[0m
- **Healthcare-specific considerations:** PHI, documented matching equity disparities across demographic groups, consent/info-blocking rules, 21st Century Cures Act, TEFCA, identity sensitivity (especially for name/gender transitions)[0m[0m
- **What you'll build:** Bulleted summary mapping to all 10 recipes[0m[0m
- **Closing transition** to Recipe 5.1[0m[0m
[0m[0m
